post_text:
After having his final outdoor track season cancelled, Michael Roberts was unable to reach his goal of setting an official school record in the 3200 meters. However, he decided to continue training on his own, and after a lot of hard work, was able to complete the 3200 meters in a time of 10:12.6, beating the official record of 10:21.1 set in 1978.

Congratulations, Michael, on becoming the fastest 3200-meter runner to ever graduate from Remsen CSD! #RemsenRamsRock

We are pleased to announce that Remsen has achieved the following ratings:

Ranking 2,847 out of 17,792 schools in the nation = 84th percentile
Ranking 269 out of 1,342 schools in the state = 80th percentile
Ranking 5 out of 26 schools in the Utica area = 81st percentile

It takes the joint effort of every student, staff member, parent, administrator, community member and Board of Education member to get us these results, great work! ğŸ‘ #RemsenRamsRock

shared_text:
Jodi Anne Richard
April 17 at 8:33 AM Â·

Good morning! Today's lesson is a time lapse because it would take too long to do it live. I went grocery shopping on Wednesday and had a big pile of cardboard to recycle. I didn't notice all the colors until I had it all in a pile and I was thinking how pretty it was. Haha! I am the self proclaimed queen of recycled art. All of my reflector tape art is made from garbage, thrown out pieces of scraps from NYS road signs. And you can often find me picking out of piles of junk people are throwing out for old wood scraps to make signs with, or old windows. I love making something beautiful out of something that was intended for a landfill. Plus, I dont like buying art supplies because they are really expensive! So today's project is garbage art! I love masks, I have a collection of them. So, I made a mask out of my recyclables. Maybe I'll do more after this dries a little! Just be very careful with any sharp objects you use, nobody needs to get hurt right now!

And you can often find me picking out of piles of junk people are throwing out for old wood scraps to make signs with, or old windows. I love making something beautiful out of something that was intended for a landfill. Plus, I dont like buying art supplies because they are really expensive! So today's project is garbage art! I love masks, I have a collection of them. So, I made a mask out of my recyclables. Maybe I'll do more after this dries a little! Just be very careful with any sharp objects you use, nobody needs to get hurt right now!

Jodi Anne Richard
April 9 at 8:09 AM Â·

Here is today's time lapse for our art lesson on OP ART. OP art is the coolest, we will talk more about it at 9:00. But, please watch this before so you can have a better idea of what we will be doing. Or, watch it later, or watch it 10 times or don't watch it at all. That, my friends, is the beauty of art. You make your own rules and if you choose to make art, that's cool. If you choose to just look at art, that's cool, too. Or you can take a nap. We are living through a pandemic and we will all deal with it differently. For me, making these videos has been an important key to my stability. But, to be honest, I haven't felt really motivated to make art in my studio. Just can't find it in my soul right now. And, that's ok. Maybe I will, maybe I won't. But I hope maybe, someone will make a little art because of these videos and find a few hours of reprise from this pandemic experience. See you at 9!

The Foundations of Technology class designed and built cranes to specific criteria to study load capacity and efficiency.

The cranes were all built with identical, limited materials. Destructive testing was then used to measure the maximum load a crane could bear before failure. The weight of the materials, along with the maximum load, was used to calculate the efficiency of each crane.

After calculations, it was determined that Al McCormack and Nate Diaz had built the most efficient crane. ğŸ—ï¸ #RemsenRamsRock
